description:
## Severity
Trivial
## Dimension
error-handling
## Location
src/tools/bash/mod.rs:117-125, 131-138
## Violation
Both reader threads use `reader.lines().map_while(Result::ok)`, which silently terminates the stream on the FIRST `Err` (typically invalid UTF-8 or transient IO error). Subsequent valid lines are dropped without notice. A child that emits binary in the middle of text output loses ALL output after that point.

Quoted (mod.rs:117-125):
```
            thread::spawn(move || {
                let reader = BufReader::new(stdout);
                for line in reader.lines().map_while(Result::ok) {
                    if let Ok(mut buf) = buffer.lock() {
                        buf.push(line);
                    }
                }
                finished_clone.store(true, Ordering::SeqCst);
            });
```

Same pattern at lines 131-138.
## Mandated refactor
1. Read raw bytes with `read_until(b'\n', ...)` and store `Vec<u8>` rather than `Vec<String>`; render with `String::from_utf8_lossy` on drain.
2. Or capture errors into a side-channel `Vec<IoError>` and surface them in `get_output`.
3. Add a test that pipes binary mid-stream and asserts subsequent text is still captured.
